{{multiple issues| {{notability|Geography|date=September 2016}} {{refimprove|date=September 2016}} {{Orphan|date=September 2016}} }} <!-- EDIT BELOW THIS LINE --> {{Infobox building | name = R. J. Mitchell Wind Tunnel | former_names = Farnborough No. 1 Tunnel | image = R. J. Mitchell Wind Tunnel.jpg | caption = Entrance of the wind tunnel | location = [[Southampton]], [[United Kingdom]] | coordinates = {{coord|50.936258|N|1.394589|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}} | start_date = | completion_date = | architect = | landlord = | owner = [[University of Southampton]] | floor_area = | floor_count = | awards = | building_type = [[Education]]al | architectural_style = | structural_system = | current_tenants = | height = | other_dimensions = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | quantity_surveyor = | main_contractor = | diameter = }}
The '''R. J. Mitchell Wind Tunnel''' is a low-speed [[wind tunnel]] which is part of the Faculty of Engineering and the Environment at the [[University of Southampton]]. It is the largest wind tunnel in University ownership in the UK.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} It is named after famed British aircraft designer [[R.J. Mitchell]].
== History == The tunnel was built in the 1930s as part of the Farnborough Royal Aircraft Establishment cluster of tunnels.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} The tunnel was purchased by the [[University of Southampton]] for a minimal fee in 1979 on the understanding that they would cover the cost of transport and recommissioning at its new site on the Highfield Campus.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} This purchase was in response to a business case put forward at the time which focused around the need for more capacity to cope with increasing motorsport demand.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} Previously the 7x5 wind tunnel had been heavily utilised by many F1 teams and a larger facility was deemed desirable to increase model scales. The tunnel was first run in Southampton in 1981{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} and was formally opened by [[R. J. Mitchell]]’s son, Gordon Mitchell.
In the 1980s and 90s the tunnel was used extensively by Formula 1 teams as well as [[Team Penske]] who developed many Indy Cars in the facility.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} In the early 00s the tunnel was able to be utilised by University students and researchers as well as a variety of customers from various industries.
In 2013 the existing building was extended to provide a new entrance area to update the look of the building while providing new facilities for users as well as wheelchair access.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.studiofourarchitects.com/wind-tunnel-university-of-southampton/|title=Wind Tunnel, University of Southampton - Studio Four Architects|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref> This extension was formally opened by [[Chris Boardman]] in January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2014/01/13_wind_tunnel_opening.page|title=Wind Tunnel Opening - Engineering and the Environment - University of Southampton|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref>
== National Wind Tunnel Facility == In January 2014 the R. J. Mitchell Wind Tunnel became a ‘[[National Wind Tunnel Facility]]’<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epsrc.ac.uk/research/facilities/access/otherfacilities/nationalwindtunnelfacility/|title=National Wind Tunnel Facility (NWTF) - EPSRC website|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref> under a government initiative announced by minister for Science and Universities [[David Willetts]]. The initiative gave 17 facilities access to a total of £13.3 million with funding coming from both [[EPSRC]] and the UK Aerodynamic Centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-25668025|title=Seven universities set up national wind tunnel facility|author=|date=9 January 2014|publisher=|accessdate=9 October 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The funding allocated to the tunnel was used to design and build a traverse system, install a combined chiller/heat pump into the circuit and also funded both a high resolution and high speed [[Particle Image Velocimetry]] (PIV) systems.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}
== Capabilities == The R. J. Mitchell Wind Tunnel is a closed test section, closed return type wind tunnel powered by a {{convert|746|kW|abbr=on}} electric motor. The test section is 3.5m wide by 2.4m high (11&nbsp;ft by 8&nbsp;ft) and the tunnel is capable of creating wind speeds of up to 40&nbsp;m/s (90&nbsp;mph).{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}} The tunnel has a moving ground installed along with dual stage boundary layer suction for ground effect or vehicle testing.
The facility has a range of possible configurations including an overhead 6-component balance, mechanised strut with in-car 6-component balance for vehicle work as well as a 2-component underfloor dynamometer that is used primarily for performance sports work. This sports work was initiated before the 2008 Beijing Olympic Games when the tunnel was an integral part of the 'Secret Squirrel Club' used to help improve the performance of the Team GB cycle team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://impact.ref.ac.uk/CaseStudies/CaseStudy.aspx?Id=44168|title=REF Case study search|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref> The success in cycling was also continued in the Winter Games when the Team GB Skeleton Bob team used the tunnel as part of a research project which resulted in [[Amy Williams]] winning Gold in Vancouver.
The facility has various data acquisition systems available including pressure scanning and PIV systems.
